            . I am in the service of Mr. John Brickell, a <rs id="t18310512-141-viclabel823" type="occupation">pawnbroker</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310512-141-victim1052 t18310512-141-viclabel823"></join>, in <placeName id="t18310512-141-crimeloc824">Tottenham-court-road</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18310512-141-crimeloc824" type="placeName" value="Tottenham-court-road"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18310512-141-crimeloc824" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310512-141-off821 t18310512-141-crimeloc824"></join>. On Wednesday, the 4th of May, about half-past six o'clock, I saw the prisoner in front of his shop; some top-boots hung outside - he appeared to lift down a pair; he walked away with them - I followed, and gave him in charge, with them in his hand.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. Q. What were the boots hanging to? A. To the blind-iron; I did not take you at the time, because I thought you would strike me - you were taken in Rathbone-place; I kept him in view till I saw the Police-constable.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310512-141-person1054">
                  GEORGE 
                  JEFFERIES
               <interp inst="t18310512-141-person1054" type="surname" value="JEFFERIES"></interp>
